3D PRINTING ALLY WAS FORMED IN JULY OF 2013 WITH ONE GOAL,

TO BRING 3D PRINTING TO ALL MANUFACTURING COMPANIES BIG AND SMALL.

3D printing can help any size company save time and money with manufacturing aids like:

Design communication for complex parts - Let your programmers, toolmakers and machinists hold a sample part to get a better visualization of what’s needed.

Drill jigs - Hold .010” true position using a drill press.

Assembly fixtures - Securely hold any shaped parts in place for safe assembly.

Inspection fixtures - Hold parts in the optimal position for inspecting in one operation.

Sample parts for CMM programming - Have programs written and proven before the parts show up.

Check fixtures - Verify part numbers on families of similar parts.

5S, 6S and Lean Manufacturing aids - Place tools where they're needed and know when they’re missing.

Short run tooling for forming aluminum - Hydro and brake press tooling.

Robotic end of arm tooling - Quickly develop and implement new tooling for robotic cells

Light duty machining fixtures for odd shaped parts - Part supports and soft jaws

Custom machine guards and personal safety guards - Keep hands out of dangerous areas in any situation

Vacuum form tooling - Quickly develop and implement tooling for light and heavy gage applications.

I am a self-taught software engineer, carpenter, musician, tinker, hacker, and maker with an insatiable curiosity for how things work, and how they can be improved. I've disassembled, hacked and modified machines and electronics since I can remember walking, and 3D printing for me is at the nexus of many of the things that inspire me, and so it is a natural fit as a hobby.

I print with a highly modified, precisely calibrated, Anet A8 running customized Marlin firmware and an RPi 3 B+ running Octopi/Octoprint. I fastened the whole bit to a 3/4 inch sheet of MDF, which was the best/cheapest "upgrade" I've done (had the MDF lying around), no bracing or frame mods have made a bigger difference. Other than that, I am running GT2 belts, toothed idlers, upgraded rods/bearings on all axis, glass bed, dual MOSFETs, PSU cover and switch, dual set screw heater block, upgraded hot bed connectors, tons of extruder mods (Noctua extruder fan, Sunon maglev part cooling fan, removable fan mod, "spaceship" cooling duct, etc.), Noctua fans on mobo/MOSFETs and PSU, and a ton of other tweaks here and there. It's basically still the stock frame, motors, mobo, PSU and most wiring, heat bed, extruder heater, carriage, and bearing blocks, with all the dodgy/cheaper bits fixed. I still only have half the price of a Prusa in it, and it prints very well, is quiet and as safe as it can be. My next rig will most likely be RAMPS-based and built from scratch, with an all-metal frame.

Después de vivir sus aventuras de campamento como monitora y coordinadora encontró la posibilidad de unir sus dos pasiones como profesora de extraescolares de robótica educativa y programación de videojuegos.

A día de hoy es la responsable del departamento de electrónica de Educatibot, donde por fin ha encontrado la posibilidad de unir y desarrollar al máximo sus dos pasiones y su habilidad.
